ates House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|TX|34}} since 2013. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nVela was born in [[Harlingen, Texas]] and raised in [[Brownsville, Texas]]. His father, [[Filemon Bartolome Vela, Sr.]], was a long-serving United States federal judge.  The Reynaldo G. Garza-Filemon B. Vela United States Courthouse in Brownsville is named in Judge Vela's honor. His mother, [[Blanca Vela|Blanca Sanchez Vela]], served as Brownsville\u2019s first female mayor from 1999 to 2003.<ref>vela.house.gov</ref><ref name=monitor>{{cite news|first=Ty|last=Johnson|title=Former Brownsville mayor, feminist 'trailblazer' Blanca Vela dies at 78 |url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/local/article_93ce870a-99d3-11e3-8d61-001a4bcf6878.html |work=[[The Monitor (Texas)]] |publisher= |date=2014-02-18 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref><ref name=kveo>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Brownsville's former and only female mayor, Blanca Vela, passes away |url=http://www.kveo.com/news/brownsvilles-former-and-only-female-mayor-blanca-vela-passes-away |work=[[KVEO]] |publisher= |date=2014-02-19 |accessdate=2014-03-13}}</ref>\n\nFilemon attended [[Saint Joseph Academy (Brownsville, Texas)|Saint Joseph Academy]] in Brownsville, Texas, and went on to graduate from [[Georgetown University]] in 1985. During his time at Georgetown, he served as an intern at the [[Federal Judicial Center]] \u2013 the research and education agency of the federal judicial system. He also served as an intern in [[Solomon P. Ortiz|Congressman Solomon P Ortiz\u2019s]] Washington, D.C. office. Vela earned his J.D. from [[University of Texas School of Law|University of Texas at Austin School of Law]] in 1987. <ref>vela.house.gov</ref>\n\n==Law career==\nFor more than 20 years, Filemon practiced law in [[South Texas]], helping countless individuals seek justice in state and federal courts across the country.  His legal practice focused on complex civil litigation. As a trial attorney, Filemon successfully represented clients who were the victims of racial discrimination, consumers who had been severely injured by defective products, and employees injured during work.\n\nSome notable cases include Earl Shinhoster v. [[Ford Motor Company]] where Vela represented the family of deceased Director of the [[NAACP]] who was killed in a car rollover accident in what was the largest wrongful death settlements in Alabama history and Robert Trevino v. [[Walmart]] where Vela represented a group of American farm workers who were told they could not shop in a Mississippi store because of discrimination against Hispanics.[4]  \n\nAs an attorney, Vela also represented several South Texas school districts. In [[Edinburg Consolidated Independent School District|Edinburg School District]] v. Landmark, Vela represented Edinburg to fight for more funding and in Pharr-San Juan-Alamo Independent School District v. Landmark, he represented the district in fighting contractors accused of building another poorly constructed school facility.\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vela.house.gov/index.php/about-filemon/full-biography |title=Full Biography |publisher=Vela.house.gov |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===2012 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2012#District 34}}\nVela decided to run in the newly created [[Texas's 34th congressional district]] as a Democrat. In the May 29 primary, Vela ranked first in an 8-candidate field with 40% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=760010 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref> In the July 31 run-off primary, Vela defeated Denise Saenz Blanchard 67%-33%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=767642 |title=Ourcampaigns.com |publisher=Ourcampaigns.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref><ref>http://enr.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/july31_163_state.htm</ref> \n\nIn the general election, Vela defeated Republican Jessica Bradshaw 62% - 36%, winning the election.<ref>{{cite web|title=TX-TopRaces-Glance-Sum|url=http://www.kxxv.com/story/20031305/tx-topraces-glance-sum?clienttype=printable|work=kxxv.com|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nIn July 2013, he decided to quit the [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]] because of his opposition to the [[John Hoeven|Hoeven]]-[[Bob Corker|Corker]] Amendment that tied border security with a [[amnesty|pathway to citizenship]]. He said \u201cerecting more border fence drives a wedge between border communities which are culturally united.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Gary |url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2013/07/rep-filemon-vela-quits-congressional-hispanic-caucus-to-protest-lawmakers-acceptance-of-border-militarization/ |title=Rep. Filemon Vela quits Congressional Hispanic Caucus to protest lawmakers\u2019 acceptance of border \u2018militarization\u2019 - Texas on the Potomac |publisher=Blog.chron.com |date=2013-07-02 |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/filemon-vela-quits-hispanic-caucus-border-surge-93676.html?hp=l8 |title=Filemon Vela quits Hispanic caucus over border surge - Seung Min Kim |publisher=Politico.Com |date=2013-07-02 |accessdate=2014-08-19}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit|Subcommittee on Livestock, Rural Development, and Credit]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n**[[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies|Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies]]\n\n==Personal life==\nVela's wife, Rose, was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] justice on Texas\u2019 13th [[Texas Courts of Appeals|Court of Appeals]] from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanchez|first=Humberto|title=113th Congress: Filemon Vela, D-Texas (34th District)|url=http://public.cq.com/docs/news/news-000004172501.html|work=public.cq.com|publisher=Congressional Quarterly, Inc.|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://vela.house.gov/ Congressman Filemon Vela]\n*[http://www.velaforcongress.com/ Filemon Vela for Congress]{{deadlink|date=March 2014}}\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Texas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Filemon_Vela_%5BD-34%5D|Filemon Vela}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = V000132 | ballot = Filemon_Vela | nndb = | votesmart = 137719 | govtrack = 412580 | opencong = 412580 | rollcall = 44902 | politifact = | fec = H2TX27190 | opensecrets = N00034349 | assets = | legistorm = | followthemoney = | ontheissues = TX/Filemon_Vela.htm | congress = filemon-vela/2167 | worldcat = | c-span = filemonvela | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | wsj = | washpo = 9636abe4-5505-11e2-bf3e-76c0a789346f }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox |\n  state=Texas|\n  district=34 |\n  before=District established |\n  start=January 3, 2013\n}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Marc Veasey]]<br><small>D-[[Texas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=420th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ann Wagner]]<br><small>R-[[Missouri]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{TX-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata\n| NAME              = Vela, Filemon, Jr.\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = Texas politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH  